I am working with a file format that contains a ZipArchive inside a Package. To access the data following code is applied:

``` c#
var outer = Package.Open(filename, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read, FileShare.Read);
var data = outer.GetPart(new Uri("/Image.data", UriKind.Relative));
var inner = new ZipArchive(data.GetStream(FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read), ZipArchiveMode.Read, true);
```
Running that code targetting netFramewok472 takes about 0.5 sec to open a 400MB file on a SMB network share over a 16Mbit network connection. Memory consumption is 42MB.

Running same code targetting netCoreApp30 on same file, took 290 sec ending up with 800MB memory consumtion.

This is a huge performance drop in access time and memory consumtion. Any suggestions where this comes from and how to workaround?

## Formatting
When trying to format timezone offset with custom [`:` delimiter](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/base-types/custom-date-and-time-format-strings?redirectedfrom=MSDN#timeSeparator) result has `":"` instead of `DateTimeFormatInfo.TimeSeparator` provided.
#### Dot separator
```csharp
var dotSeparatedCulture = new CultureInfo("")
{
    DateTimeFormat = { TimeSeparator = "." },
};
var result = DateTime.UtcNow.ToString("zzz", dotSeparatedCulture);
Assert.AreEqual("+00.00", result);
// Assert.AreEqual failed. Expected:<+00.00>. Actual:<+00:00>.  
```
#### Empty separator
```csharp
var emptySeparatorCulture = new CultureInfo("")
{
    DateTimeFormat = { TimeSeparator = "" },
};
var result = DateTime.UtcNow.ToString("zzz", emptySeparatorCulture);

Assert.AreEqual("+0000", result);
// Assert.AreEqual failed. Expected:<+0000>. Actual:<+00:00>.  
```
Problem is in the function [`System.DateTimeFormat.FormatCustomizedTimeZone`](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/465da74726664728b690ce4d0086d56f59187a1f/src/Common/src/CoreLib/System/Globalization/DateTimeFormat.cs#L824):
```csharp
// 'zzz*' or longer format e.g "-07:30"
result.AppendFormat(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture, ":{0:00}", offset.Minutes);
```
where `:` is appended instead of `DateTimeFormatInfo.TimeSeparator`

## Parsing
Same issue with parsing. When trying to parse timezone offset with custom `:` delimiter a `System.FormatException` is thrown:
#### Dot separator
```csharp
var offset = TimeZoneInfo.Utc.GetUtcOffset(DateTime.UtcNow);
var customInvariantCulture = new CultureInfo("")
{
    DateTimeFormat = { TimeSeparator = "." },
};
var result = DateTime.ParseExact("+00.00", "zzz", customInvariantCulture);
var resultOffset = TimeZoneInfo.Utc.GetUtcOffset(result.ToUniversalTime());
Assert.AreEqual(offset, resultOffset);
// threw exception:  System.FormatException: String '+00.00' was not recognized as a valid DateTime at System.DateTime.ParseExact(String s, String format, IFormatProvider provider)
```
Problem is in the function [`System.DateTimeParse.ParseTimeZoneOffset`](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/5bc7c43f61842f19247cef40ba88f7fb395b956d/src/Common/src/CoreLib/System/Globalization/DateTimeParse.cs#L3268):
```csharp
if (str.Match(":"))
{
    // Found ':'
    if (!ParseDigits(ref str, 2, out minuteOffset))
    {
        return false;
    }
}
```
where `":"` is matched instead of `DateTimeFormatInfo.TimeSeparator`
However since it's optional the following code works:
#### Empty separator [Works]
```csharp
var offset = TimeZoneInfo.Utc.GetUtcOffset(DateTime.UtcNow);
var customInvariantCulture = new CultureInfo("")
{
    DateTimeFormat = { TimeSeparator = "" },
};
var result = DateTime.ParseExact("+0000", "zzz", customInvariantCulture);
var resultOffset = TimeZoneInfo.Utc.GetUtcOffset(result.ToUniversalTime());
Assert.AreEqual(offset, resultOffset);
```

**Version Used**: 

VS 16.3.8
Netstandard 2.1

**Steps to Reproduce**:

1.
Create a new .netstandard 2.1 project, add `<Nullable>enable</Nullable>` and `<LangVersion>8.0</LangVersion>` to the project file

2.

Add the following class:

```
    public sealed class Bytes
    {
        public static readonly Bytes Empty = new Bytes();

        [return: NotNullIfNotNull("left")]
        [return: NotNullIfNotNull("right")]
        public static Bytes? operator +(Bytes? left, Bytes? right) => left == null ? right : right == null ? left : Empty;

        public static Bytes Example()
        {
            return Empty + Empty;
        }
    }

```

3. Compile

**Expected Behavior**:

No warnings emitted

**Actual Behavior**:

"[CS8603] Possible null reference return" emitted for the method Example()

